When it comes to circuits, there are two ways circuits can be built, series and parallel.

A parallel circuit has more than one path where current can flow through, as voltage is the same through each path, the current will break up along each parallel path but recombine when the paths meet up again. For example, if one lightbulb burns out in a series circuit, the entire circuit is broken, while in a parallel circuit, if a lightbulb in one path is broken, that won’t affect the other paths.
